<h2>Samsung Galaxy Ring — Best for Android</h2>
<img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1434494878577-86c23bcb06b9?w=800&q=80" alt="Samsung Galaxy Ring technology" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;aspect-ratio:16/9;object-fit:cover;margin-bottom:20px;" loading="lazy"/>
<p>The Samsung Galaxy Ring integrates seamlessly with Samsung Health and Galaxy Watch. If you already have Samsung devices, data synergy is its biggest advantage. Sleep analysis is solid though it doesn't reach Oura's level, and battery lasts 7 days.</p>
<div class="pros-cons">
  <div class="pros-box"><span class="pros-box__label">✓ PROS</span><ul><li>No monthly subscription</li><li>Seamless Samsung integration</li><li>7-day battery</li></ul></div>
  <div class="cons-box"><span class="cons-box__label">✗ CONS</span><ul><li>Android only</li><li>Less accurate than Oura for HRV</li></ul></div>
</div>
<a href="https://www.samsung.com/us/smartphones/galaxy-ring/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cta-btn" style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:28px;">Check Samsung Galaxy Ring price →</a>
<h2>Ultrahuman Ring Air — Best for iPhone</h2>
<p>The Ultrahuman Ring Air is the most recommendable no-subscription alternative for iPhone users. Its app is well-designed, sleep analysis is accurate, and it's the lightest ring on the market (2.4 grams). It doesn't reach Oura's HRV level, but for most users the difference isn't noticeable.</p>
<div class="pros-cons">
  <div class="pros-box"><span class="pros-box__label">✓ PROS</span><ul><li>Compatible with iOS and Android</li><li>Lightest on the market</li><li>No subscription</li></ul></div>
  <div class="cons-box"><span class="cons-box__label">✗ CONS</span><ul><li>HRV less accurate than Oura</li><li>App less polished than Samsung</li></ul></div>
</div>
