<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">Is Oura Ring's subscription worth paying?</p><p class="faq-item__a">It depends on your use. If you want deep insights and personalized recommendations, yes. If you just want to see sleep and activity data, no-subscription alternatives are sufficient.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">Will Samsung Galaxy Ring ever work with iPhone?</p><p class="faq-item__a">No confirmed plans. Samsung has stated Galaxy Ring is designed for the Android/Samsung ecosystem. For iPhone, Ultrahuman or Oura are better options.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">Are there cheap smart rings that actually work?</p><p class="faq-item__a">The RingConn Gen 2 Air at around $149 offers decent tracking with no subscription. It's not as accurate as the others but it's an affordable entry into the smart ring world.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">How much do you save per year by choosing no-subscription?</p><p class="faq-item__a">Oura Ring costs $349 + $72/year = $421 the first year. Samsung Galaxy Ring is $299 one-time. Over 3 years the difference exceeds $210.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">Do the alternatives get software updates over time?</p><p class="faq-item__a">Yes, all update their app and algorithms. Samsung and Ultrahuman release regular software updates that improve features at no additional cost.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">Where to buy these alternatives in the US?</p><p class="faq-item__a">Samsung Galaxy Ring on samsung.com/us, Best Buy and Amazon. Ultrahuman Ring Air on ultrahuman.com. RingConn on ringconn.com with international shipping.</p></div>
